<h1 id="week-4--recap-and-rehearsals">Week 4 | Recap and rehearsals</h1>

<p><strong>Group rehearsals of Composition 1</strong>
Groups rehearse in readiness for Composition 1 performance next week.</p>

<p>Have you you formed your groups? If you haven, let‚Äôs create some now.</p>

<p>Remember to check to module guide for what you need to have in your first composition. Here again:</p>

<p>As you have experienced last week, working together on a composition requires organisation. Please take the time to play/rehearse together in order to address the above criteria for this task:</p>

<p><strong>Identifiable musical form</strong></p>

<p>Make sure there are a few sections in your composition which everyone in your group knows about. Last week you choose to use a sound effect to indicate a move to the next section. This is good if you do not want everyone to keep track of where exactly you are in the piece. As discussed in week 2, you could also think about other ways of communication, using physical gestures, signs on paper, etc‚Ä¶ There are also ways to synchronise software on different machines, however to do this on Logic (most of your preferred DAW) doesn‚Äôt seem to be too reliable, but explore if you have the time‚Ä¶</p>

<p><strong>Clear harmonic structure</strong></p>

<p>A simple idea would be to use one scale/mode, which everyone utilises. This way you do not have to worry about certain parts of your composition to sound disharmonious, unless this is the aim. To make sure you have an interesting vertical harmonic structure, employ some chord progressions in your composition (use at least four chords).</p>

<p><strong>Clear melodies</strong></p>

<p>As discussed in week 03, here ‚Äòmelody‚Äô indicates horizontal harmonic structure.</p>

<p>‚Äú‚Ä¶at least four chords.‚Äù</p>

<p>This can mean two things:</p>

<p>1) You utilise 4 different types of chords in your part of the composition.</p>

<p>2) The notes you play in your composition form a chord with someone else‚Äôs notes (played on another computer) and these are a part of a chord progression. (Here again at least 4 different types of chords.)</p>

<p>Here an approach:</p>

<p>BEFORE YOUR REHEARSAL</p>

<p>1) Form a group</p>

<p>2) Find out when people are available</p>
<ul>
  <li>e.g. open a facebook group conversation;</li>
</ul>

<p>3) Book a room</p>
<ul>
  <li>think about whether you need speakers, minirigs (are they charged?), amps, submixers, how you connect to them, etc‚Ä¶</li>
</ul>

<p>4) Book equipment if needed from technicians</p>
<ul>
  <li>in advance if you are rehearsing on weekend or in the evening;</li>
</ul>

<p>REHEARSAL</p>

<p>1) Don‚Äôt be late.
Make sure you had some food, drinks, emptied your bladder ‚Ä¶ so you can fully focus on the task and your collaboration.</p>

<p>2) Find a scale/mode that you all stick to.</p>
<ul>
  <li>perhaps introduce some modulation if you‚Äôd like, where you composition moves from one scale to another and perhaps back, ‚Ä¶</li>
</ul>

<p>3) Outline a rough form/structure.
e.g. ABBA;</p>

<p>4) Come up with a tempo.</p>
<ul>
  <li>perhaps a beat that everyone could follow;</li>
  <li>remember you can change the time signature or event the tempo anywhere in your composition if you‚Äôd like;</li>
</ul>

<p>5) Find out how you indicate the end/beginning of a new part in your form.</p>
<ul>
  <li>e.g. sound, gesture, ‚Ä¶</li>
</ul>

<p>6) Create motifs.</p>
<ul>
  <li>perhaps even slightly different ones for each of you;</li>
  <li>the same melody can be played in reverse, notes randomly played, slower, faster, ‚Ä¶</li>
</ul>

<p>7) Create phrases</p>
<ul>
  <li>make conversations with your instruments, come up with a story for your piece;</li>
</ul>

<p>8) Edit, refine, self-reflect, discuss.</p>

<p>9) Edit, refine, self-reflect, discuss.</p>

<p>10) Edit, refine, self-reflect, discuss.</p>

<p>‚Ä¶</p>

