<h4 id="introduction-to-task-2">Introduction to Task 2</h4>
<p>From the <a href="https://www.dropbox.com/s/v53vp96ycwjhr58/mod000556-laptop-performance_mod_guide_2017.pdf?dl=0">module guide</a>:</p>

<p><img src="http://www.tedor.info/extra/LaPerf/Task%2002%20-%20highlights.jpg" alt="Task 2 Guide" /></p>

<p>This assignment invites you to experiment with <br />
1) different types of <a href="http://www.tedor.info/teaching/mod003619-music-for-the-moving-image/mod003619-w03/">listening modes</a> and with<br />
2) creating unusual sounds, motifs, phrases‚Ä¶ a composition.</p>

<p>Let‚Äôs examine the keywords in the task description:</p>

<dl>
  <dt><em>‚ÄòStructured composition‚Äô</em> that <em>‚Äòhas a clear and identifiable beginning, middle and end‚Äô</em></dt>
  <dd>This means the composition‚Äôs form is restricted to three parts. This can be ABC, ABB‚Äô, ACC‚Äô, AA‚ÄôA‚Äô‚Äô, ‚Ä¶ Note that the guide also suggest that the length of these parts should be the same. Do you remember how long your composition can be? Check <a href="https://www.dropbox.com/s/v53vp96ycwjhr58/mod000556-laptop-performance_mod_guide_2017.pdf?dl=0">here</a> if you forgot.</dd>
  <dt><em>‚ÄòFocuses on noise and drone‚Äô</em></dt>
  <dd>‚Äò‚Ä¶ rather than pulse‚Äô here indicates, that the composition shouldn‚Äôt be beat driven like the compositions you prepared for task 1. It instead should be based on musical expressions that create some kind of continuous flow (drone music), where the music is rhythmically still and slowly evolving.</dd>
</dl>

